Eight people are missing after an earthquake struck a copper mine in western Poland, the mine's operator wrote on Twitter. "At the moment, 8 miners are being sought after the shock in ZG Rudna," KGHM said.Â "The rescue operation is still in progress." Seven employees were taken to hospital, the company said. The quake occurred at a depth of 770 meters (2,520 feet) shortly before 2 p.m. local time (1300 UTC). Mining operations began at the Rudna mine near the city of Polkowice in 1974. The company says it extracts an average of 12 million tonnes of cooper ore a year. More to come...